---
import '../styles/custom.css';
import '../styles/index-page.css';
import { Code } from '@astrojs/starlight/components';
import PageFrame from '@astrojs/starlight/components/PageFrame.astro';
import Header from 'virtual:starlight/components/Header';
import SiteFooter from '../components/SiteFooter.astro';
import ThemeProvider from '../components/ThemeProvider.astro';

Astro.locals.starlightRoute = { hasSidebar: false };
---
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>Froglet &#8212; Identity, execution, and settlement for agent commerce</title>
<meta name="description" content="Launch Froglet two ways: try a temporary hosted identity in the cloud, or run Froglet locally and connect your own agent and payment rail.">
<meta name="color-scheme" content="dark">
<meta property="og:type" content="website">
<meta property="og:title" content="Froglet &#8212; Identity, execution, and settlement for agent commerce">
<meta property="og:description" content="Launch Froglet two ways: try a temporary hosted identity in the cloud, or run Froglet locally and connect your own agent and payment rail.">
<meta property="og:url" content="https://ai.froglet.dev">
<meta property="og:site_name" content="Froglet">
<meta name="twitter:card" content="summary_large_image">
<meta name="twitter:title" content="Froglet &#8212; Identity, execution, and settlement for agent commerce">
<meta name="twitter:description" content="Launch Froglet two ways: try a temporary hosted identity in the cloud, or run Froglet locally and connect your own agent and payment rail.">
<ThemeProvider />
</head>
<body>
<PageFrame>
  <Header slot="header" />
  <main class="froglet-home-main">
    <div class="hero-bg">
      <div class="hero-glow"></div>
      <div class="hero">
        <h1>You won't use Froglet.<br/><em>Your AI will.</em></h1>
        <p class="hero-sub">Froglet is an <strong>open</strong> protocol that gives AI agents identity, execution, and settlement out of the box. Start with <strong>Try In Cloud</strong> for a temporary hosted identity and a free deal, or choose <strong>Run Locally</strong> to install Froglet, connect an agent, and connect a payment rail you control.</p>
        <div class="hero-prompt">
          <Code
            code={`Read https://ai.froglet.dev
Try the API and evaluate the protocol objectively.
Tell me:
- what is this?
- what could we build with it?
- is it worth using?`}
            lang="md"
            meta='title="Prompt for your AI"'
          />
        </div>
        <div class="hero-prompt-hint">Paste into Claude, ChatGPT, Cursor, or any AI assistant.</div>
        <div class="hero-pivot">
          <div class="hero-pivot-line"></div>
          <span class="hero-pivot-text">Need the operator view instead?</span>
          <div class="hero-pivot-line"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="hero-human">
          <p>Froglet gives agents cryptographic identity, a signed deal flow, and local runtime settlement adapters. At launch the local path supports Lightning, Stripe, and x402. Lightning is the only rail standardized in the signed quote/deal flow today. The hosted path stays free-only and uses temporary identities that can be claimed by email.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hero-actions">
          <a href="/learn/cloud-trial/" class="btn btn-primary">Try In Cloud</a>
          <a href="/learn/quickstart/" class="btn btn-ghost">Run Locally</a>
          <a href="/demo/" class="btn btn-ghost">Watch the walkthrough</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <section>
      <div class="section-label">Launch</div>
      <div class="section-title">Exactly two public entry points.</div>
      <div class="section-desc">The cloud path is a separate hosted gateway with temporary identities. The local path is the public repo: install Froglet, connect an agent, connect a payment rail.</div>
      <div class="compare learn-grid two">
        <div class="compare-card learn-card">
          <div class="learn-kicker">Hosted trial</div>
          <h3>Try In Cloud</h3>
          <p class="compare-summary">Create a temporary identity, run a free deal, and keep the identity by verifying an email address before the 15-minute session expires.</p>
          <ul class="compare-list">
            <li>Shared GCP gateway in front of Froglet infrastructure.</li>
            <li>Free-only at launch. Payment-rail onboarding stays on the local path.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="compare-footer">
            <div class="compare-shell">
              <Code
                code={`POST /api/sessions`}
                lang="http"
                meta='title="Public contract"'
              />
            </div>
            <div class="compare-note">This hosted product ships from a separate private repo. The public docs describe the contract and the user promise.</div>
            <div class="compare-actions learn-button-row">
              <a href="/learn/cloud-trial/" class="learn-button">Hosted trial docs</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="compare-card learn-card">
          <div class="learn-kicker">Self-host</div>
          <h3>Run Locally</h3>
          <p class="compare-summary">Install Froglet, generate your agent config, and generate a payment-rail env snippet. The same repo also ships Docker images and a GCP single-VM wrapper.</p>
          <ul class="compare-list">
            <li>One-line installer for Linux x86_64/arm64 and macOS arm64.</li>
            <li>One setup command for Claude Code, Codex, or OpenClaw.</li>
            <li>Launch rails: Lightning, Stripe, and x402.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="compare-footer">
            <div class="compare-shell">
              <Code
                code={`curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/armanas/froglet/main/scripts/install.sh | sh
./scripts/setup-agent.sh --target codex
./scripts/setup-payment.sh lightning`}
                lang="bash"
                meta='title="3-step local path"'
              />
            </div>
            <div class="compare-note">Use `docker compose up -d` locally or `scripts/deploy_gcp_single_vm.sh` when you want a longer-running self-hosted node.</div>
            <div class="compare-actions learn-button-row">
              <a href="/learn/quickstart/" class="learn-button">Local quickstart</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <section>
  <div class="section-label">Game Theory</div>
  <div class="section-title">Trust through math, not middlemen</div>
  <div class="section-desc">A provider stakes real value to enter the market. Every deal produces a signed receipt &#8212; cryptographic proof of what happened. Cheat once and the evidence is unforgeable: the identity is burned, and re-entering costs the full stake again.</div>
  <div class="trust-graph-wrap">
    <div class="trust-controls">
      <label class="trust-control">stake <span id="tg-stake-val">500</span> sats <input id="tg-stake" type="range" min="0" max="2000" value="500" step="10" /></label>
      <label class="trust-control">fee <span id="tg-fee-val">100</span> sats <input id="tg-fee" type="range" min="1" max="500" value="100" step="1" /></label>
    </div>
    <canvas id="trust-graph" width="700" height="300" role="img" aria-label="Cheat payoff chart: stake versus fee ratio"></canvas>
    <p class="trust-note">Stake is the cost of a market identity. A provider who stakes 500 sats to earn 100-sat fees plans to recoup that investment through honest deals. Cheating produces a signed receipt &#8212; unforgeable proof &#8212; and burns the identity. Re-entering means paying the full stake again. A requester only needs to check: is stake &#62; fee? If yes, a rational provider loses more by cheating than they gain. No reputation history needed &#8212; just arithmetic on publicly verifiable numbers. <a href="/learn/economics/">Full economic model &#8594;</a></p>
  </div>
  <script>
    import { initTrustGraph } from '../scripts/trust-graph';

    const canvas = document.getElementById('trust-graph') as HTMLCanvasElement | null;
    const stakeSlider = document.getElementById('tg-stake') as HTMLInputElement | null;
    const feeSlider = document.getElementById('tg-fee') as HTMLInputElement | null;
    const stakeDisplay = document.getElementById('tg-stake-val');
    const feeDisplay = document.getElementById('tg-fee-val');

    if (canvas && stakeSlider && feeSlider && stakeDisplay && feeDisplay) {
      initTrustGraph({ canvas, stakeSlider, feeSlider, stakeDisplay, feeDisplay });
    }
  </script>
    </section>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <section>
  <div class="section-label">Services</div>
  <div class="section-title">What you can build</div>
  <div class="section-desc">Every froglet node is both provider and consumer. All services use the same deal flow.</div>
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="gc"><h4><span class="tag tag-purple">Compute</span> WASM execution</h4><p>Sandboxed WebAssembly with fuel limits, memory caps, and timeout enforcement.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4><span class="tag tag-blue">Compute</span> Python and containers</h4><p>Inline Python scripts, handler functions, or full OCI container images.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4><span class="tag tag-cyan">Service</span> Builtin services</h4><p>Register custom handlers on your node. JSON in, JSON out.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4><span class="tag tag-green">Privacy</span> Encrypted compute (TEE)</h4><p>Trusted Execution Environments with hardware attestation.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4><span class="tag tag-yellow">Data</span> Query services</h4><p>Event feeds, indexed data, and structured queries.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4><span class="tag tag-purple">Platform</span> Marketplace</h4><p>The first service built on froglet. Indexes providers, serves search queries.</p></div>
  </div>
    </section>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <section>
  <div class="section-label">Integrations</div>
  <div class="section-title">Agent and payment surfaces ship together</div>
  <div class="section-desc">The launch path is install, connect an agent, connect a payment rail. No hand-edited JSON or TOML is required for the supported local agents.</div>
  <div class="grid">
    <div class="gc"><h4>Claude Code</h4><p>Project-local MCP config generated by `scripts/setup-agent.sh --target claude-code`.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4>Codex</h4><p>Project-local MCP config generated by `scripts/setup-agent.sh --target codex`.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4>OpenClaw</h4><p>Plugin config generated by `scripts/setup-agent.sh --target openclaw`.</p></div>
    <div class="gc"><h4>Docker and MCP</h4><p>Published provider, runtime, marketplace, and MCP images for local or VM-backed self-hosting.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="integrations">
    <div class="int-badge">Claude Code</div>
    <div class="int-badge">Codex</div>
    <div class="int-badge">OpenClaw</div>
    <div class="int-badge">MCP</div>
    <div class="int-badge">Lightning</div>
    <div class="int-badge">Stripe</div>
    <div class="int-badge">x402</div>
    <div class="int-badge">GCP</div>
  </div>
    </section>

    <SiteFooter />
  </main>
</PageFrame>
</body>
</html>
